scenarioDescription:
The WASP-161 Exoplanetary System


Overview

WASP-161 is a star with 1.39 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.71 times its radius. It is located 1130.0000776 light years away from the solar system.

WASP-161 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the WASP-161 system

WASP-161 b

WASP-161 b was discovered by the SuperWASP-South observatory using the Transit method. The mass of WASP-161 b is 791.3967 times the mass of Earth. The radius of WASP-161 b is 12.812 that of Earth. At more than 10 Earth masses, WASP-161 b is an ice giant, a planet that is made up mostly of volatiles like water, amonia and methane, and enveloped by a dense hydrogen and helium atmosphere, much like Uranus and Neptune in our solar system. At more than 50 Earth masses, WASP-161 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
